This is not a simple question.

1. No.  - There are robots.txt, and prohibited segments, you cannot get at.

2. No.  - There are aspects of the web that are deep, behind databases, 
that heritrix is not designed to hit.

3. No. - There are video formats that are problematic to get through 
normal web download, so it can&#39;t get them.

And so on.

That said, yes, it can crawl everywhere.

The configuration you use is a bunch of machines, where bunch is defined 
as as many as you can afford.

Expect about 150K worth of hardware, to crawl 10B sites in 2 months.
Some good fast 4 core processor, 32G or more memory, maybe 8T - 16T disk 
on each of 20 - 40 systems.
If you want to go faster, scale up your systems.

Set up a hash mapped crawl config, use some seedlist that most interests 
you, and go.

I&#39;ve done this a few dozen times, building archive sets.

Maybe I&#39;ll go write a FAQ for it, Gordon says I should.

John

